2c6ab595-b1f3-48c2-a9e9-c09d8ade576d.text: Retrieval of Atmospheric Aerosol Optical Depth From AVHRR Over Land With Global Coverage Using Machine Learning Method Xiaoqing Tian ,LingGao,JunLi,LinChen , Jingjing Ren, and Chengcai Li Abstract — Aerosols play an important role in global climate change, which requires long-term data records. Advanced very high-resolution radiometer (AVHRR) provides continuous obser-vations for up to 40 years since 1979, which makes it worthwhile to retrieve aerosol optical depth (AOD) from AVHRR over land. A novel algorithm for retrieving AOD from AVHRR is developed based on the machine learning (ML) method. The AVHRR observations from pathfinder atmospheres–extended (PATMOS-x) Level-2 dataset and corresponding AOD products (0.55 μ m ) from moderate resolution imaging spectroradiome-ter (MODIS) in 2014 are used as training data. And AOD products in three years (2015, 2006, and 1998) named AVHRR XGB-AOD were generated for evaluation. Comparisons show that the AVHRR XGB-AOD is consistent with the MODIS AOD with correlation coefficients greater than 0.80 and RMSE less than 0.18 for most months in 2015 and 2006. The temporal and spatial characteristics from AVHRR XGB-AOD are similar to those from the MODIS AOD, but those from the previous AVHRR AOD with deep blue (DB) algorithm are significantly different. Validation with AERONET indicates that more than 68% of the matchups fall within expected error [EE, ± (0.05 ± 0.25 × AOD AERONET ) ] in 2015 and 2006, while the fraction is 66% in 1998. Compared to the DB algorithm, the ML-based algorithm performs better in high-AOD conditions over vegetated regions, such as in Southeast Asia, where the DB algorithm significantly underestimates. In low-AOD conditions, the ML-based algorithm performs better over western North America and Australia, where the aerosol composition varies

Long-term data records of aerosol are needed to improve aerosol modeling and better understand how aerosols affect climate change. Atmospheric Aerosol Optical Depth (AOD) is one of the most important parameters to describe the content and extinction characteristics of atmospheric aerosol. Ground-based observations can provide the AOD record with a high temporal resolution, but the scarcity of observation sites makes it difficult to reveal the variation of spatial distribu-tion. Satellite remote sensors, such as advanced very high-resolution radiometer (AVHRR), moderate resolution imaging spectroradiometer (MODIS), total ozone mapping spectrome-ters (TOMS), multi-angle imaging spectroradiometer (MISR), etc., can obtain AOD observations with large coverage. Among these sensors, only AVHRR and TOMS can provide historical observations since 1979. However, for TOMS, the channels are all in the ultraviolet spectral region and are more sensitive to the absorbing aerosols, which results in larger uncertainty due to being more sensitive to aerosol height. Therefore, it is very important to use AVHRR for deriving the long-term record of global aerosol. 1558-0644 © 2021 I EEE. These algorithms mentioned above focused on specific cases and limited regions. Hsu et al. [10] extended the deep blue (DB) algorithm to AVHRR by using 0.63 μ m channel instead of 0.46 μ m used in the MODIS DB algorithm. By applying the extended DB algorithm, they developed a near-global dataset covering 1989–1990 (NOAA-11), 1995– 1999 (NOAA-14), and 2006–2011 (NOAA-18). However, this dataset has a significant difference with MODIS AOD, espe-cially, it underestimates AOD during summer over vegetated surfaces [11]. As mentioned above, the physical algorithm has limitations in the retrieval of AOD from AVHRR over land. Some studies attempted to use statistical methods for retrieving AOD from AVHRR over land. Gao et al. [12] used a multiple regression method for deriving AOD over China from AVHRR and generated a long-term AOD dataset over mainland China from 1982 to 2011 [13]. Using MODIS AOD as a reference, the retrieved AOD from statistical models has better accuracy than those from the DB algorithm over eastern and southern China. The algorithm based on multiple regression performs reliably over the China region, which offers the potential to develop a similar approach for retrieving AVHRR AOD over land at global coverage. In this study, an algorithm based on the ML method to retrieve AOD from AVHRR over land is developed; the objective is to derive AOD CDR over land from AVHRR at global coverage. Although AERONET AOD is more accurate than MODIS AOD, the global distribution of AERONET sites is extremely uneven, concentrated over North Amer-ica and Europe, which is insu fficient for characterizing aerosol over the globe. Therefore, the AOD from MODIS MYD04 is selected as the response variable (label data), and the collocated AVHRR observations and other auxiliary data are predictors. Theoretically, the accuracy of AVHRR AOD retrieved based on ML methods cannot exceed that of the response variable, MODIS AOD. The main purpose of this article is to retrieve AVHRR AOD for historical data records with reasonable accuracy when compared with MODIS AOD. RF, Light Gradient Boosting Machine (LightGBM), and eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost), which are widely used in atmospheric sciences, are considered for retrieving AOD in this study. AVHRR Data The AVHRR Pathfinder Atmospheres–Extended (PATMOS-x) dataset used in this article is currently generated from reprocessing measurements from AVHRR sensors flown on NOAA series polar-orbiting satellite (http://cimss.ssec.wisc.edu/patmosx/). AVHRR sensor has six spectral channels at visible (channel 1 at 0.63 μ m, channel 2 at 0.86 μ m ) , near-infrared (channel 3a at 1.6 μ m, channel 3b at 3.75 μ m ) , and thermal infrared (channel 4at11 μ m, channel 5 at 12 μ m ) . The viewing swath width of AVHRR is 2800 km. PATMOS-x Level-2 dataset provides global daily grid data with spatial resolution 0.1 ◦ by 0.1 ◦ , including reflectance of visible channels, brightness temperatures (BT) of infrared channels, and cloud property products. In this study, AVHRR apparent reflectance at 0.63, 0.86, and 3.75 μ m, and the corresponding observation angles including solar zenith angle, satellite viewing zenith angle, and relative azimuth angle are used to develop an algorithm for retrieving AOD. NDVI derived from AVHRR is used to represent surface information, which is one of the NOAA CDR with a high resolution of 0.05 ◦ by 0.05 ◦ (https://climatedataguide.ucar.edu/climate-data/ndvi-normalized-difference-vegetation-index-noaa-avhrr). C. MODIS Data MODIS is a key instrument aboard the Terra and Aqua satellites. The equatorial crossing times of the Terra and Aqua are about 10:30 A . M . and 1:30 P . M ., respectively. The MODIS has 36 different wavelength channels and provides global observation data at least twice every day with a viewing swath of 2330 km. Over land, the dark target (DT) algorithm retrieves aerosol properties by using the empirical relationship between visible channels (0.47, 0.65 μ m ) reflectance and near-infrared (2.1 μ m ) reflectance to determine the surface reflectance in visible channels [24]–[27]. But this empirical relationship is satisfied only over a dark surface, such as dense vegetation. For a bright surface, the DB algorithm was developed using the blue spectral channel (i.e., wavelength < 0.5 μ m ) to retrieve AOD [28], [29]. The uncertainty of the MODIS AOD is expected to be  AOD =± ( 0 . 05 ± 0 . 15 × AOD ) over land [25], [30], which is one of the widely used products to study environmental pollution and characterize the spatial and temporal characteristics of global aerosols. Both of the MODIS and AVHRR are the instruments aboard afternoon satellites observing the same atmosphere almost simultaneously, and channels of AVHRR are similar to those used in the MODIS DT algorithm. Besides model training, an independent MYD04 dataset is also selected to test the accuracy of the retrievals from AVHRR on a pixel basis, and MODIS AOD (1 ◦ by 1 ◦ ) is used to compare the temporal and spatial variations of global AOD distributions. D. AERONET Data AOD provided by AERONET is used to verify the accuracy of retrieved AOD from AVHRR in this study. AERONET AOD is measured directly by ground-based sunphotometer CE-318, which is not affected by aerosol model, surface type, and other assumptions [32]. The estimated accuracy of the AERONET AOD product is ± 0.02 [32]. There are three level data available, i.e., level 0 (unscreened), level 1.5 (cloud-screened), and level 2.0 (cloud-screened and quality-assured) (http://aeronet.gsfc.nasa.gov/). AVHRR AOD Dataset From DB Algorithm DB algorithm is developed to retrieve AOD from MODIS over bright land [28], [29]. Hsu et al. [10] applied an extended DB algorithm to AVHRR and developed the near-global AVHRR DB-AOD. The key of the DB algorithm is to build the surface database at visible channels. In the AVHRR DB algorithm, there are two appro aches to estimate the surface reflectance depending on whether the surface type is bright or vegetated. For bright surfaces, a global seasonally varying database is constructed using the minimum reflectance method. AVHRR lacks the channel of 412 nm (which is used in the MODIS DB algorithm), so 630 nm is used instead. The surface is brighter at 630 nm than 412 nm, which results in larger AOD uncertainty. AVHRR DB-AOD is the only dataset that provided the long-term CDR over land from AVHRR with global coverage in our knowledge. This dataset covers 1989–1990 (NOAA-11), 1995–1999 (NOAA-14), and 2006–2011 (NOAA-18). The primary retrieved parameters (L2) are AOD at 550 and 630 nm, as well as the corresponding pixel-level QA, flags provided in 5 min granules at approximately 8.8 km × 8.8 km pixel size at the sub-satellite point. The QA flag is at a variant integer from 0 to 3, where 0 represents no retrieval, 1 represents ‘poor’, 2, 3 indicate ‘fair’ and good, respectively. ML Methods In previous studies, tree-based algorithms, such as RF, LightGBM, and XGBoost have exhibited good performance in air pollutant assessment [34]–[36]. Accordingly, RF, Light-GBM, and XGBoost are considered in our primary study, and there is a concise explanation of the three algorithms. The RF algorithm is a combination of a series of decision trees in which each tree is an independent random sampling, and all trees have the same distribution. It evaluates the splits of all available variables at each node and then selects the split (variable) which results in less inhomogeneity. The algorithm gradually converges with an increase in the number of trees [37]. Before training a model, the RF algorithm generates a bootstrap sample from original data and random selection of a subset of predictors. Thereby, this algorithm reduces the overfitting problem by injected randomness [37]. XGBoost is based on a gradient boosting decision tree (GBDT), in which each classifier is designed to reduce the residual of the previous classifier. In the DB algorithm, a spatial variability filter based on the reflectance at 630 nm within the area of a 3 × 3 pixel is employed for AVHRR, which filters out most puffy clouds and cloud edges [10]. In addition to the influence of cloud detection, the viewing swath width of MODIS is narrower than that of AVHRR, resulting in some orbital gaps in MODIS observations at low latitudes. DB algorithm performs slightly better over Europe, which may be since atmospheric correction and estimating the sur- face reflectance using physical methods is more accurate in low-AOD vegetated conditions, where the aerosol type is not too variable in time. And the dependence of apparent reflectance on AOD is generally weaker in very low AODs ( < 0.3), such as in Europe [42], which leads to greater uncer-tainty in ML methods. V. C ONCLUSION An algorithm based on ML method has been developed to retrieve AOD from AVHRR over land at global coverage. AVHRR apparent reflectance, observation angle, and other auxiliary information are the i nput variables in the algorithm. For the training model, AOD at 0.55 μ m from MODIS Aqua is the response variable, since channels of AVHRR are similar to those used in the MODIS DT algorithm, and observe the same atmosphere almost simultaneously. XGBoost per-formed with higher accuracy and e fficiency than RF, therefore, the algorithm based on XGBoost is used to retrieve AOD from AVHRR over land with global coverage. Over vegetated high-AOD conditions, the XGBoost algorithm performs better than the DB algorithm, where the DB algorithm signif-icantly underestimates the AOD over regions, such as Southeast Asia and Southeast China. Over areas where the composition of aerosol varies greatly, XGBoost also performs better, such as over western North America and Australia, which may benefit from the fact that aerosol model assumption is not needed in the retrieval process. Over vegetated low-AOD conditions, XGBoost algorithm performs relatively poorly than the DB algo-rithm, such as over Europe and eastern North Amer-ica. Statistical methods have greater uncertainty in the retrieval of extremely low AOD values. Over these areas, the composition of aerosol is not too variable in time, so the atmospheric correction and estimating the surface reflectance by using physical methods is more accurate.
